Analysis of Trapping Length
¶

$$ l_{\mathrm{p}} \simeq 2\times\texttt{per}^2 \tag{1}\label{1}$$

where $l_{\mathrm{p}}$ is the persistence length and $\texttt{per}$ is a computational variable. The approximation is accurate for larger $\texttt{per}$.

In [1]:
import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

#warnings.filterwarnings("ignore") # "default", etc.

Parameters A; Low Number of Trials¶

  • $\texttt{per} = \{[0,2],\,2.5,\,3\}$ - Make this $0$ to have a freely jointed walk, otherwise the bigger this is the stiffer the chain is.

  • $\Delta{\texttt{per}} = 0.2$

  • $\texttt{iter}=1,\!000$ - number of walks to simulate

  • $\texttt{vis}=0$

<ipython-input-14-b492524eed29>:2: RuntimeWarning: divide by zero encountered in true_divide
  plt.plot((m1[i]/tpt[i])/ave_lt[i], m2[i], color='black')

Based on the plot above, as $\texttt{per}$ increases, the following decreases;

$$ \left[l_{\mathrm{t}} \cdot \left(2\times\texttt{per}^2\right)^{-1}\right] / \left\langle l_{\mathrm{t}} \right\rangle \tag{2}\label{2} $$

as expected since $\texttt{per}$ is in the denomicator. In otherwords, as the persistance length increases, $\eqref{2}$ decreseases since,

$$ \left[l_{\mathrm{t}} \cdot \left(2\times\texttt{per}^2\right)^{-1}\right] / \left\langle l_{\mathrm{t}} \right\rangle \simeq \dfrac{l_{\mathrm{t}}}{l_{\mathrm{p}} \left\langle l_{\mathrm{t}} \right\rangle} \tag{3}\label{3} $$

$\hspace{1cm}$...unfortunately, this plot does not seem meaningful...

Now noramlizing the the plots for $\text{# of simulations}$ vs $l_{\mathrm{t}} \,/ \left\langle l_{\mathrm{t}} \right\rangle$ and fitting a function to it; try:

$$f(x) = a\left(x-\frac{7}{\left\langle l_{\mathrm{t}} \right\rangle}\right)^{b} \exp\left[-c\left(x - \frac{7}{\left\langle l_{\mathrm{t}}\right\rangle}\right)^{\vphantom{l}}\!\right] \tag{4}\label{4}$$
where the number $7$ represents the minimum trapping length (could possibly be $8$, $6$ is used in the code). Do this for all the plots corresponding to different $l_{\mathrm{p}}$. Moreover, from here on define,

$$ l_{\mathrm{p}}^{\prime} \,\equiv\, 2\times\texttt{per}^2 \,\simeq\, l_{\mathrm{p}} \tag{5}\label{5} $$

Normalizing the area under the curves¶

The normalization constant $A$:

$$ \begin{align*} 1 = A\int f(x) \,dx \qquad\implies\qquad A &= \dfrac{1}{\left[\sum{f(x)}\right] \cdot \Delta x} \end{align*} $$

(This is interesting...) Instead,

$$ \text{total area} \propto xy \qquad\implies\qquad 1 \backsimeq \texttt{xdata}\times\left(\frac{\texttt{ydata}}{\text{total area}}\right) $$

in other words, to normalize the area under a curve, divide the $\texttt{ydata}$ by the original total area under the curve.

Radius of Gyration¶

$$ R_{\mathrm{g}} = \sqrt{\sum_\imath \sigma_\imath^2 } \tag{6}\label{6} $$

where $\sigma_\imath^2$ is the variance of the $\imath^{\mathrm{th}}$ coordinate's data.

In [29]:
Rg2 = sio.loadmat('data/rg.mat')['rg']

$\underline{R}_\mathrm{g}$ is an $m\times n$ matrix whose the rows are chains with different trapping lengths and the columns are different walks. The matrix of $R_\mathrm{g}$, i.e. $\boldsymbol{{R}_\mathrm{g}}$, where $l$ represents the length and $w$ represents the walk:

$$ \begin{align} \boldsymbol{{R}_\mathrm{g}} = \begin{pmatrix} w_0l_0 & w_1l_0 & \cdots & w_nl_1 \\ w_0l_1 & w_1l_1 & \cdots & w_nl_2 \\ w_0l_2 & w_1l_2 & \cdots & w_nl_3 \\ \vdots & \ddots & \cdots & \vdots \\ w_0l_m & w_1l_m& \cdots & w_nl_m \end{pmatrix} \tag{7}\label{7} \end{align} $$

Here, $m$ is len(Rg) which is just $m = 669$; the number of columns (len(Rg)[#]) is $n = 16190$.

In [30]:
for i in range(len(Rg2[0])):      # "for i in range of the number of walks"
    plt.plot(Rg2[:,i])
    
plt.ylabel(r"$R_{\mathrm{g}}^2$", fontsize=20)
plt.xlabel(r"$l_{\mathrm{t}}$", fontsize=20)
plt.tight_layout()
#plt.savefig("plots/radius_of_gyration/all_rg2_vs_lt_iter=16190.pdf", bbox_inches='tight')
plt.show()

Finding the population average as a function of trapping length; the average of all those curves, not including the parts that no longer exist.¶

Population mean, $\mu$;

$$ \mu = \dfrac{\sum X}{N} \tag{8}\label{8} $$

where $X$ is the individual items in the group and $N$ is the number of items in the group.

    In the matrix for $\boldsymbol{{R}_\mathrm{g}}$, eliminate the zeros from each walk as they idicate exactly nothing. If the zeros were to not be eliminated, the resulting graph of $\left\langle R_{\mathrm{g}} \right\rangle$ vs $l_{\mathrm{t}}$ would look like:

In [31]:
ave_Rg2_WRONG = np.mean(Rg2, axis=1)     # average the rows; i.e., average the different lengths from each independent walk
plt.plot(ave_Rg2_WRONG, color='black')
plt.show()

But of course, this would be incorrect. (I just thought it would be interesting to see what it looks like, clearly all the zeros are effecting it in a Gaussian way!)

The average radius of gyration¶

The Matlab code that finds $\left\langle \underline{R}_{\mathrm{g}} \right\rangle^2$ should be:

for i = 1:669
  temp = Rg2(i,:);
  temp = temp(temp > 0);
  Rg2_mean(i) = mean(temp);
end
In [32]:
ave_Rg2 = []
temp = []

# start from 1 because first row is just a bunch of zeros...
for m in range(1,len(Rg2)):       # "for m in range the numner of rows of matrix Rg" (669)
    for n in range(len(Rg2[0])):  # "for n in range the mumber of columns of matrix Rg" (16190)  
        if Rg2[m,n] != 0:
            temp.append(Rg2[m,n])
    ave_Rg2.append(sum(temp)/len(temp))
    temp = []
del temp


plt.plot(ave_Rg2)
plt.ylabel(r"$\left\langle R_{\mathrm{g}}^2 \right\rangle$", fontsize=25)
plt.xlabel(r"$l_{\mathrm{t}}$", fontsize=25)
plt.tight_layout()
#plt.savefig("plots/radius_of_gyration/ave_rg2_vs_lt_iter=16190.pdf", bbox_inches='tight')
plt.show()

Note that up until here, it was actually $R_{\mathrm{g}}^2$ instead of $R_{\mathrm{g}}$!

After graphing the ${\langle {R}_{\mathrm{g}}^2 \rangle}$ related plots, to the straight part of the graph, fit a power function $h(x) = ax^b.$ But the interesting quantity is $\langle {R}_{\mathrm{g}} \rangle$ itself and not its square. One cannot simply divide the power law by the exponent of the average radius of gyration as $\langle \zeta \rangle \neq \langle \zeta^b \rangle^{1/b}.$

    One solution would be to go back to the beginning and to take the square root of all the elements of $ \boldsymbol{R^2_\mathrm{g}}$; but, it would be more efficient to simply divide the power law found for $\langle R_{\mathrm{g}}^2\rangle\!\left(l_\mathrm{t}\right)$ by $2$, even though it is not the same as $\langle {R}_{\mathrm{g}} \rangle$! This is OK because for a large amount of data they will be the same; the variance is $\langle R_\mathrm{g}^2\rangle - \langle R_\mathrm{g}\rangle^2$ and gets relatively smaller with more data. (You can try it yourself with smaller numbers and see how different the results are.)

$$ \lim_{n\to\infty} \sigma^2 = 0 \tag{9}\label{9} $$

where $n$ is number of simulations.

In [33]:
def h(x, a,b):
    return a*x**b

plt.plot(ave_Rg2, 'b--', label='data')
lt = np.linspace(0, len(ave_Rg2)-1, len(ave_Rg2))

# lt is linear and increases by 1 starting from 0, so lt[300] = 300.

popt, pcov = curve_fit(h, lt[0:300], ave_Rg2[0:300])


plt.plot(lt[0:300], h(lt[0:300], *popt), 'r-', label=r'fit $\left(ax^b\right)$: $a=%5.3f,~b=%5.3f$' % tuple(popt))
plt.ylabel(r"$\left\langle R_{\mathrm{g}}^2 \right\rangle$", fontsize=25)
plt.xlabel(r"$l_{\mathrm{t}}$", fontsize=25)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.legend()
#plt.savefig("plots/radius_of_gyration/ave_rg2_vs_lt-fit_iter=16190.pdf", bbox_inches='tight')
plt.show()

print('   a =', "%0.18f" % popt[0], '±', "%.18f" % pcov[0,0]**0.5) #2ND HALF IS FIT UNCERTAINTY
print('   b =', "%0.18f" % popt[1], '±', "%.18f" % pcov[1,1]**0.5)

   a = 0.689996112710368870 ± 0.005841939348850574
   b = 1.351312331902958075 ± 0.001556724769333615

And so the power law for $R_{\mathrm{g}}\!\left(l_\mathrm{t}\right)$ is ${ \tfrac{b}{2} = \underline{0.675656165951479}. }$

By eyeballing this plot, it appears that the "straight part" is between $\log l_\mathrm{t} \approx 0.5$ and $\log l_\mathrm{t} \approx 2.5$; the power function $h$ will be fit to that region. To find the indeces of values closest to these numbers, either print out log_lt or use np.where.
    Using np.where to find the index of the first element $\geq 0.5$:

>>> np.where(log_lt >= 0.5)[0][0]

which returns 3. Then, using this method to find the index of the first element which is $\leq 2.5$:

>>> np.where(log_lt <= 2.5)[0][-1]

which returns 315.
